SIMPLE: inquiry
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inquiry
<hw>In*quir"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Inquiries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[See
<er>Inquire</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>enquiry</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of inquiring; a
seeking for information by asking questions; interrogation; a question
or questioning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He could no path nor track of foot descry,⟦br⟧
Nor by <qex>inquiry</qex> learn, nor guess by aim.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The men which were sent from Cornelius had made <qex>inquiry</qex>
for Simon's house, and stood before the gate.</q> <rj><qau>Acts x.
17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Search for truth, information, or knowledge;
examination into facts or principles; research; investigation; <as>as,
physical <ex>inquiries</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that is wanting to the perfection of this art will undoubtedly
be found, if able men . . . will make <qex>inquiry</qex> into it.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Court of inquiry</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Court</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Writ of inquiry</b></col>, <cd>a writ
issued in certain actions at law, where the defendant has suffered
judgment to pass against him by default, in order to ascertain and
assess the plaintiff's damages, where they can not readily be
ascertained by mere calculation.</cd> <au>Burrill.</au></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Interrogation; interrogatory; question; query;
scrutiny; investigation; research; examination.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inquisible</ent>⟦br⟧
